  "texts": [
    "Singing in choruses can be based on consonances (nice sounding, \"sweet, \" non-tense) or dissonances (rough sounding, tense) combination of sounds or intervals.",
    "Scholars have mostly concentrated on the use of nice sounding consonances (e.g., Tasuku et al., 2010; Crespo-Bojorque and Toro, 2016).",
    "I suggest in the context of the defense paying special attention to dissonances.",
    "Singing in dissonant intervals greatly contributes to the creation of a more robust sound.",
    "In the light of behavioral ecology, dissonant intervals are the most potent vocal signal for creating (1) the loudest possible sound, (2) the most attention-grabbing sound, and (3) the most effective \"Beau Geste\" sound (when a small group wants to make an audio impression of a much larger group; Wren, 1924; Harrington, 1989; Tripovich et al., 2008)."
